{"title_page": "A9 road (Zimbabwe)", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|country=ZWE\n|type=A\n|route=9\n}}\n'''A9 Road (Zimbabwe)''' is a national highways running from [[Mutare]] to [[Mbalabala]]. The road begins in [[Mutare]] {{coord|18.983492|S|32.66002|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A9 Highway, Zimbabwe_Mutare|format=dms}}  and runs south-west through [[Nyanyadzi]], [[Birchenough Bridge]], [[Masvingo]], [[Mashava]], [[Zvishavane]], [[Filabusi]] and ends at [[Mbalabala]] where it joins the (A6) [[Bulawayo-Beit Bridge Highway]] near the 61.5&nbsp;km peg. (   {{coord|20.44375|S|29.041006|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A9 Highway,  Zimbabwe_Mbalabala|format=dms}} )<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160410110807/http://routeplannermap.com/driving-directions/road-map-from-filabusi+zimbabwe-to-masvingo+zimbabwe-driving-directions-car-route-planner |Car route from Filabusi, Zimbabwe to Masvingo, Zimbabwe|Filabusi, Zimbabwe: Head northeast 4.8 km:                                                                    Turn right onto A9 85.5 km:                                                                                                                                            Turn left to stay on A9 94.4 km:                                                                                                                                            Turn right onto A4/A9 0.9 km:                                                                                                                                                   Turn left onto Rhus Ave 0.2 km:                                                                                                                                       Turn right 0.3 km Masvingo,                                                                                                                                     Zimbabwe] Route Planner|Car route|Retrieved 20 2016</ref> It has a total of just less than {{convert|513|km|mi}}, which is about a 6 hours 15 minute drive.\n\n==Background==\nA9 Highway is an inter-city and an inter-district primary road divided into two link roads namely P4 (Masvingo-Mutare Highway) and P7 (Masvingo-Mbalabala Highway) to suite the trunk road linking system.\n\n==Operations==\nThe A9 Highway is the shortest route from [[Botswana]] through the [[Plumtree, Zimbabwe|Plumtree Border Post]] to [[Mutare]], and from south-western [[Zambia]] through the [[Victoria Falls|Victoria Falls Border Post]] but the greater part of the A9 Highway is not designated as the regional road corridor. \nThe P4 part of this highway plays an important role in linking regional traffic from [[South Africa]] to [[Mutare]] and to parts of central-western [[Mozambique]] through the [[Beitbridge|Beitbridge Border Post]]. \nP4 begins in [[Masvingo]] and runs north-east most of way through [[Birchenough Bridge]] and [[Nyanyadzi]] before linking with A3 Highway in [[Mutare]].\n\nThe P7 part connects [[Masvingo]] with [[Mashava]], [[Zvishavane]], [[Filabusi]]. It ends at [[Mbalabala]] where it forms a T-junction with A6 to link with [[Gwanda]], [[Esigodini]] and [[Bulawayo]]. At [[Zvishavane]] P7 intersects with A18 Highway that runs from [[Gweru to Zvishavane]].\n\nROAD NAMES SOURCE MAP:  [http://www.afdb.org/fileadmin/uploads/afdb/Documents/Generic-Documents/11.%20Zimbabwe%20Report_Chapter%209.pdf |Chapter 9: Road Transport Services and Infrastructure]\n\nExternal Link.\n\n==Junctions==\n\u2022\tThe first major junction is from Mutare is Chimanimani turn-off where the [[A10Road (Zimbabwe)|A10 Highway]] branches left (east) to [[Chimanimani]] and Cashel. (  {{coord|19.506136|S|32.530792|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A9/A10 Highways junction|format=dms}} )\n\n\u2022\tThe second junction is just three and half kilometres before [[Birchenough Bridge]] where A16 Highway to [[Chipinga]] branches left. ({{coord|19.951189 |S|32.36808|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A16/A9 Highways junction|format=dms}}  )\n\n\u2022\tThe third junction is in [[Masvingo]] where A9 Highway intersects with [[A4 road (Zimbabwe)|A4 Highway]] which runs from [[Harare]] to [[Beitbridge]].  (  {{coord|20.0720092|S |30.834566|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A9/A4 Highways junction|format=dms}} )\n\n\u2022\tThe fourth junction is at [[Zvishavane]] turn-off where it intersects with [[A18 road (Zimbabwe)|A18 Highway]] that runs from [[Gweru]] to [[Zvishavane]].  ( {{coord|20.31421|S |30.052465|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A9/A18 Highways junction|format=dms}} )\nThere are however smaller junctions all the way from [[Mutare]] to [[Mbalabala]] which plan a very important role in the trunk road system.\n\n==Major Waypoints==\n\u2022\t[[Birchenough Bridge]]   ( {{coord|19.990668|S|30.995527|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=Birchnough Bridge|format=dms}} )   Birchnough Bridge is one of those places tourist do not want to miss.\n\n\u2022\t[[Masvingo]] is the largest waypoint on this road. It is the capital city of [[Masvingo Province]] and home to the [[Great Zimbabwe]] ruins.\n\n\u2022\t[[Zvishavane]] is just off the road at the junction of this [[Masvingo-Mbalabala Highway]] and the [[Gweru-Zvishavane Highway]].\n\n\u2022\t[[Filabusi]]\n\n\u2022\t[[Mbalabala]] though the end of the A9 Highway is not usually the destination of motorists using this road. So it will be another waypoint for those travelling to either [[Gwanda]] or [[Bulawayo]].\n\n==See also==\n\u2022\t[[P4 Road (Zimbabwe)|P4 Highway]]\n\n\u2022\t[[P7 Road (Zimbabwe)|P7 Highway]]\n\n\u2022\t[[R1 Road (Zimbabwe)|R1 Highway]]\n\n\u2022\t[[Chirundu-Beitbridge Highway]] \n\n*       [[ZINARA]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Roads in Zimbabwe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|country=ZWE\n|type=A\n|route=9\n}}\n'''A9 Road (Zimbabwe)''' is a national highways running from [[Mutare]] to [[Mbalabala]]. The road begins in [[Mutare]] {{coord|18.983492|S|32.66002|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A9 Highway, Zimbabwe_Mutare|format=dms}}  and runs south-west through [[Nyanyadzi]], [[Birchenough Bridge]], [[Masvingo]], [[Mashava]], [[Zvishavane]], [[Filabusi]] and ends at [[Mbalabala]] where it joins the (A6) [[Bulawayo-Beit Bridge Highway]] near the 61.5&nbsp;km peg. (   {{coord|20.44375|S|29.041006|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A9 Highway,  Zimbabwe_Mbalabala|format=dms}} )<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160410110807/http://routeplannermap.com/driving-directions/road-map-from-filabusi+zimbabwe-to-masvingo+zimbabwe-driving-directions-car-route-planner |Car route from Filabusi, Zimbabwe to Masvingo, Zimbabwe|Filabusi, Zimbabwe: Head northeast 4.8 km:                                                                    Turn right onto A9 85.5 km:                                                                                                                                            Turn left to stay on A9 94.4 km:                                                                                                                                            Turn right onto A4/A9 0.9 km:                                                                                                                                                   Turn left onto Rhus Ave 0.2 km:                                                                                                                                       Turn right 0.3 km Masvingo,                                                                                                                                     Zimbabwe] Route Planner|Car route|Retrieved 20 2016</ref> It has a total of just less than {{convert|513|km|mi}}, which is about a 6 hours 15 minute drive.\n\n==Background==\nA9 Highway is an inter-city and an inter-district primary road divided into two link roads namely P4 (Masvingo-Mutare Highway) and P7 (Masvingo-Mbalabala Highway) to suite the trunk road linking system.\n\n==Operations==\nThe A9 Highway is the shortest route from [[Botswana]] through the [[Plumtree, Zimbabwe|Plumtree Border Post]] to [[Mutare]], and from south-western [[Zambia]] through the [[Victoria Falls|Victoria Falls Border Post]] but the greater part of the A9 Highway is not designated as the regional road corridor. \nThe P4 part of this highway plays an important role in linking regional traffic from [[South Africa]] to [[Mutare]] and to parts of central-western [[Mozambique]] through the [[Beitbridge|Beitbridge Border Post]]. \nP4 begins in [[Masvingo]] and runs north-east most of way through [[Birchenough Bridge]] and [[Nyanyadzi]] before linking with A3 Highway in [[Mutare]].\n\nThe P7 part connects [[Masvingo]] with [[Mashava]], [[Zvishavane]], [[Filabusi]]. It ends at [[Mbalabala]] where it forms a T-junction with A6 to link with [[Gwanda]], [[Esigodini]] and [[Bulawayo]]. At [[Zvishavane]] P7 intersects with A18 Highway that runs from [[Gweru to Zvishavane]].\n\nROAD NAMES SOURCE MAP:  [http://www.afdb.org/fileadmin/uploads/afdb/Documents/Generic-Documents/11.%20Zimbabwe%20Report_Chapter%209.pdf |Chapter 9: Road Transport Services and Infrastructure]\n\nExternal Link.\n\n==Junctions==\n\u2022\tThe first major junction is from Mutare is Chimanimani turn-off where the [[A10Road (Zimbabwe)|A10 Highway]] branches left (east) to [[Chimanimani]] and Cashel. (  {{coord|19.506136|S|32.530792|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A9/A10 Highways junction|format=dms}} )\n\n\u2022\tThe second junction is just three and half kilometres before [[Birchenough bridge]] where A16 Highway to [[Chipinga]] branches left. ({{coord|19.951189 |S|32.36808|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A16/A9 Highways junction|format=dms}}  )\n\n\u2022\tThe third junction is in [[Masvingo]] where A9 Highway intersects with [[A4 road (Zimbabwe)|A4 Highway]] which runs from [[Harare]] to [[Beitbridge]].  (  {{coord|20.0720092|S |30.834566|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A9/A4 Highways junction|format=dms}} )\n\n\u2022\tThe fourth junction is at [[Zvishavane]] turn-off where it intersects with [[A18 road (Zimbabwe)|A18 Highway]] that runs from [[Gweru]] to [[Zvishavane]].  ( {{coord|20.31421|S |30.052465|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=A9/A18 Highways junction|format=dms}} )\nThere are however smaller junctions all the way from [[Mutare]] to [[Mbalabala]] which plan a very important role in the trunk road system.\n\n==Major Waypoints==\n\u2022\t[[Birchenough Bridge]]   ( {{coord|19.990668|S|30.995527|E|region:ZW_type:landmark|name=Birchnough Bridge|format=dms}} )   Birchnough Bridge is one of those places tourist do not want to miss.\n\n\u2022\t[[Masvingo]] is the largest waypoint on this road. It is the capital city of [[Masvingo Province]] and home to the [[Great Zimbabwe]] ruins.\n\n\u2022\t[[Zvishavane]] is just off the road at the junction of this [[Masvingo-Mbalabala Highway]] and the [[Gweru-Zvishavane Highway]].\n\n\u2022\t[[Filabusi]]\n\n\u2022\t[[Mbalabala]] though the end of the A9 Highway is not usually the destination of motorists using this road. So it will be another waypoint for those travelling to either [[Gwanda]] or [[Bulawayo]].\n\n==See also==\n\u2022\t[[P4 Road (Zimbabwe)|P4 Highway]]\n\n\u2022\t[[P7 Road (Zimbabwe)|P7 Highway]]\n\n\u2022\t[[R1 Road (Zimbabwe)|R1 Highway]]\n\n\u2022\t[[Chirundu-Beitbridge Highway]] \n\n*       [[ZINARA]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Roads in Zimbabwe]]\n", "name_user": "Tom Radulovich", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJunctions:fix link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A9_road_(Zimbabwe)"}
{"title_page": "Washington High School (Atlanta)", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name=  Booker T. Washington High School\n|image= Washington high school.JPG\n|motto= \"One Family, One Destiny\"\n|streetaddress= 45 White House Dr.\n|city=          [[Atlanta]]\n|state=         [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n|zipcode= 30314\n|country = United States\n|district= [[Atlanta Public Schools]]\n|website= {{URL|https://www.atlantapublicschools.us/btw}}\n|superintendent=  Meria Joel Carstarphen\n|principal= Angela Coaxum-Young\n|schooltype=    Public, [[University-preparatory school|college preparatory]], [[Exam school|exam]], 21st-century small learning communities\n|grades=        [[Ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n|language=      [[American English|English]]\n|area= Historic Washington Park\n|campus=          Urban\n|mascot=    Bulldog\n|colors=  {{color box|blue}} {{color box|white}}\n|founded= 1924\n|ratio= 13.65<ref name=NCES/>\n|staff= 52.90 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|enrollment= 722 (2017\u201318)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=1300120&ID=130012004174|title=Booker T. Washington High School|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Booker T. Washington High School\n  | nrhp_type =\n  | image =\n  | caption =\n  | location= 45 Whitehouse Dr. SW, [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|33|45|12|N|84|25|18|W|region:US-GA_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Atlanta, Georgia#USA Georgia#USA\n  | built = 1924\n  | architect = Wachendorff, Eugene C.\n  | architecture = Medieval eclectic\n  | added = March 18, 1986\n  | area = {{convert|21.4|acre}}\n  | governing_body = Local\n  | refnum = 86000437<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n| designated_other1_name = Atlanta Landmark Building\n| designated_other1_date = October 14, 1989\n| designated_other1_abbr = ALB\n| designated_other1_link = List of historic buildings and districts designated by the City of Atlanta\n| designated_other1_color= #aaccff\n}}\n\n'''Booker T. Washington High School''', named for the famous educator,<ref>{{cite web|title=Booker T. Washington, 1856-1915|url=http://docsouth.unc.edu/fpn/washington/bio.html|work=Documenting the American South|publisher=The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|accessdate=7 September 2011}}</ref> opened in September 1924 under the auspices of the [[Atlanta Board of Education]], with the late Charles Lincoln Harper as principal. It was the first public high school for [[African-American]]s in the [[Georgia (U.S. state)|state of Georgia]] and the [[Atlanta Public Schools]] system.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://apskids.org/washington/ Untitled Document<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nBooker T. Washington High School was transformed into four small schools. Starting in the fall of 2014, the school transitioned back to the original one school, with four assistant principals, one academy leader, and one principal.\n\n==Administration==\n* Angela Coaxum-Young, Principal\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Atlanta Trip 130.JPG|thumb|left]]\nDesigned by Atlanta-born architect [[Eugene C. Wachendorff]], the building incorporates medieval and Byzantine elements, including the dramatic main entrance with five arches in two tiers. Six additions have been made to the original four-story building, which is situated on {{convert|21.4|acre|m2}} of land. The building is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\nIt is fitting that visitors pass the statue of the school's namesake on the way to the entrance.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/atlanta/boo.htm|title=Booker T. Washington High School--Atlanta: A National Register of Historic Places Travel Itinerary|website=www.nps.gov|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> One of the foremost black educators of the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Booker T. Washington was born into slavery in 1856 on a small farm in Virginia. He founded the [[Tuskegee University|Tuskegee Institute]] in 1881. \n\nIn 1927, the only exact replica of the Booker T. Washington monument at [[Tuskegee University]] in Alabama was erected at the school's entrance. The statue of Washington, called \"Booker T. Washington Lifting the Veil of Ignorance,\" is a replica of the original bronze at the Tuskegee Institute by sculptor Charles Keck. The inscription reads: \"He lifted the veil of ignorance from his people and pointed the way to progress through education and industry.\" <ref name=\":0\" />\n\nToday, the school, which was placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1986, boasts an enrollment of more than 1600 students and a faculty and staff of more than 100.\n\nRecent visitors to the historic institution have included [[South Africa]]n Archbishop [[Desmond Tutu]], activist [[Jesse Jackson]], civil rights pioneer [[Rosa Parks]], and President [[George W. Bush]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2002/01/images/20020131-7-1.html|title=Visiting Martin Luther King's President alma mater, George W. Bush speaks to students, faculty, and guests during a visit to Booker T. Washington High School in Atlanta, Ga. Jan 31, 2002. \"One way you can help is to find a child who needs somebody older in their life who can put their arm around them and say, \"I love you,\" \"There's hope for you,\" \"What can I do to help you succeed in America?'\" White House photo by Eric Draper.|website=georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/georgia/cascade/alma-powell-designates-booker-t-washington-high-as-fi633bf6e966|title=Alma Powell Designates Booker T. Washington High as First APS Promise Place School|date=2011-06-16|website=Cascade, GA Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nThe school serves as a cornerstone of Atlanta Public School's comprehensive reform program, Project GRAD (Graduation Really Achieves Dreams). The project aims to increase the number of inner-city students who graduate and go to college.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Washington Early College===\nBooker T. Washington High School-Early College is one of the newest early college small schools in the Atlanta Public School System.  The premise behind the early college concept is to afford students the opportunity to obtain college credits while going to high school.  BTWHS-EC aims to prepare students to pursue post-secondary education at some of the top universities and colleges in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlantapublicschools.us/domain/11274|title=Early College / Overview|last=|first=|date=|website=http|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the core program of study, students are required to take the following classes to meet the requirements of the Early College School:\n* Early College Seminar\n* Early College Math\n* Early College English\n* Early College Social Studies\n* Early College Science\n\n===Washington Banking, Finance, and Investment===\nThe Booker T. Washington High School Banking, Finance and Investment Small School (BFI) gives BTW high school students an opportunity to learn about and prepare for college careers in business and finance. Emphasis is placed on a college preparatory curriculum that is directly linked to the business world.\n\nThis school prepares students for careers in business and finance with challenging courses. It focuses on broad, transferable skills, with an emphasis on financial industry elements such as accounting, financial planning, management, banking, credit, economics, money management, technology, investments, and insurance. In addition to their required courses, BFI students take one or two specialized courses each semester and a college-level course in their senior year. Students also participate in job shadowing experiences and paid internships.\n\nBFI is a part of the National Academy Foundation's Academy of Finance. This foundation assists in establishing an ongoing relationship that involves corporate executives, school personnel, parents, and students, and results in paid internships, scholarships, and employment opportunities. Students are provided opportunities to enter into paid internships with local financial service companies during the summer of their senior year, and many offers of part-time employment during the school year are provided.  BFI also has the Institute of Student Achievement (ISA) as its intermediary partner. This organization supports the school's planning process, curriculum development, leadership development, and overall development of the small learning communities.\n\n===Washington Health, Science, and Nutrition===\nThe Booker T. Washington High School of Health Science and Nutrition (BTWHSN) provides an interdisciplinary curriculum with a healthcare and nutrition concentration through in-depth investigation, hands-on discovery, experimentation, and inquiry-based learning. Through a four-year program of study, students have the opportunity to:\n\n* Undergo a rigorous and relevant curriculum and receive in-depth instruction designed to ensure that all students meet the graduation requirements of the Atlanta Public Schools system while affording them multiple opportunities for postsecondary study.\n* Gain college credit through dual enrollment and advanced placement courses.\n* Explore career interest in various nutrition and healthcare-related fields.\n* Gain invaluable knowledge, skills, and experiences through medical seminars, internships, and health science field trips.\n* Partake in an array of shadowing opportunities and hands-on modules.\n\nBooker T. Washington High School of Health Science and Nutrition offers two career pathways: Therapeutic Services and Nutrition & Food Science.\n\n==Feeder patterns==\n\n* Elementary schools: Herndon and Bethune\n* Middle schools: Kennedy, Sylvan, and Brown\n\n==Local School Council==\n\nThe property and business of the Booker T. Washington High School Local Council is managed by seven school council members, of whom two are parents or guardians of students enrolled in the school, two are teachers, and two are business education partners. The principal serves as chairperson of the Local School Council, which meets on the first Monday of each month from 9:00-10:00 am in the second-floor conference room at the school.<ref>[http://apskids.org/washington/Local%20School%20Council.htm Untitled Document<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Student activities==\n\n===Clubs and organizations===\n{{Div col|colwidth=27em}}\n* Academic Enrichment Team\n* Band/Auxiliaries\n* Bad-To-The-Bone Dance Team\n* [[Beta Club]]\n* Bulldog RAW (Recycling at Washington)\n* [[National Honor Society]]\n* Chess Club\n* Chorus\n* Dance Ensemble\n* Debate Team\n* [[Future Business Leaders of America]] (FBLA)\n* French Club\n* [[Future Educators of America]] (FEA)\n* [[Glee Club]]\n* [[Health Occupations Students of America]] (HOSA)\n* [[Mu Alpha Theta]] (Mathematics Honor Society)\n* Photography/Videography Club\n* Spanish Club\n* Stock Market\n* Student Government Association\n* Student Support Team\n* ''Washingtonian'' newspaper and yearbook team\n{{colend}}\n\n===Athletics===\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Football\n* Softball\n* Baseball\n* Track & field\n* Cross country\n* Cheerleading\n* Soccer\n* Volleyball\n* Golf\n* Basketball\n* Band\n* Swimming\n* Tennis<ref>[http://apskids.org/washington/Activities.htm Untitled Document<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\n===Religion===\n* [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] - civil rights leader\n\n===Arts and entertainment===\n* [[Lil Baby]] - rapper, singer\n* [[Raymond Andrews]] - novelist\n* [[Leslie C. Brown|Les Brown]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - motivational speaker\n* [[Bruce Bruce]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - actor, comedian\n* [[Lee Moses ]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - musician\n* [[Jean Carne]]<ref name=\"Alumni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.btwbulldogs.com/Fame.html|title=Walk of Fame|publisher=btwBulldogs|accessdate=2009-05-02 | url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731102136/http://www.btwbulldogs.com/Fame.html |archive-date=July 31, 2013}}</ref> - singer\n* [[Nipsey Russell|Julius \"Nipsey\" Russell]]<ref name=scottAJC /> - actor, comedian, dancer\n* [[Ken Sagoes]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - actor\n* [[Young Thug]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/>- rapper, singer\n* [[Lena Horne]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - actor, singer\n\n===Government and politics===\n* [[Leroy Johnson (Georgia politician)|Leroy Johnson]]<ref name=scottAJC>{{cite news|title=Washington High: 50 Years of Learning |author=Scott, Peter |date=January 6, 1974 |newspaper=[[Atlanta Constitution]] | page=14C | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22895911/washington_high_50_years_of_learning/ | via=[[newspapers.com]] | access-date=November 15, 2018 | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115194320/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/22895911/washington_high_50_years_of_learning/ | archive-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref> - Georgia State Senator \n* [[Louis Wade Sullivan]] - former Secretary of Health and Human Services under President [[George H. W. Bush]]\n\n===Science and medicine===\n* [[Asa G. Yancey Sr.]]<ref name=scottAJC /> - physician associated with [[Emory University]] and [[Grady Hospital]]\n\n===Sports===\n* [[Donn Clendenon]]<ref name=scottAJC /> - former professional baseball player\n* [[Lanard Copeland]] - [[Philadelphia 76ers]]/NBL Australia\n* [[Joe Douse]] - baseball pitcher\n* [[Reshad Jones]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - [[Miami Dolphins]] (NFL)\n* [[Chico Renfroe]]<ref name=scottAJC /> - baseball player and sportscaster\n* [[Jabari Smith]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - [[Sacramento Kings]] (NBA)\n* [[Lawrence Smith (American football)]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - [[Baltimore Ravens]] (NFL)\n* [[Elmore Spencer]] - [[Los Angeles Clippers]] (NBA)\n* [[Walter Stith]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - [[Buffalo Bills]] (NFL)\n* [[George \"Duke\" Robinson]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - [[Carolina Panthers]] (NFL)\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Fulton County, Georgia]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Jay Winston Driskell, Jr. ''Schooling Jim Crow: The Fight for Atlanta's Booker T. Washington High School and the Roots of Black Protest Politics.'' Charlottesville, VA: University of Virginia Press, 2014.\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official|https://www.atlantapublicschools.us/btw}}\n* [http://srt5.atlantapublicschools.us/washingtonbfi/ Washington School of Banking, Finance and Investment]\n* [http://srt5.atlantapublicschools.us/washingtonec/ Booker T. Washington Early College High School]\n* [http://srt5.atlantapublicschools.us/washingtonhsn/ Booker T. Washington High School of Health Science and Nutrition]\n* [http://srt5.atlantapublicschools.us/washingtonsa/ Washington Senior Academy]\n* [http://srt5.atlantapublicschools.us/ Atlanta Public Schools, Office of High Schools]\n\n{{GHSA Class AAA Region 5}}\n{{Atlanta Public Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Historically segregated African-American schools in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:School buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:School buildings completed in 1924]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1924]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Atlanta]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name=  Booker T. Washington High School\n|image= Washington high school.JPG\n|motto= \"One Family, One Destiny\"\n|streetaddress= 45 White House Dr.\n|city=          [[Atlanta]]\n|state=         [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n|zipcode= 30314\n|country = United States\n|district= [[Atlanta Public Schools]]\n|website= {{URL|https://www.atlantapublicschools.us/btw}}\n|superintendent=  Meria Joel Carstarphen\n|principal= Angela Coaxum-Young\n|schooltype=    Public, [[University-preparatory school|college preparatory]], [[Exam school|exam]], 21st-century small learning communities\n|grades=        [[Ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n|language=      [[American English|English]]\n|area= Historic Washington Park\n|campus=          Urban\n|mascot=    Bulldog\n|colors=  {{color box|blue}} {{color box|white}}\n|founded= 1924\n|ratio= 13.65<ref name=NCES/>\n|staff= 52.90 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|enrollment= 722 (2017\u201318)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=1300120&ID=130012004174|title=Booker T. Washington High School|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Booker T. Washington High School\n  | nrhp_type =\n  | image =\n  | caption =\n  | location= 45 Whitehouse Dr. SW, [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|33|45|12|N|84|25|18|W|region:US-GA_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Atlanta, Georgia#USA Georgia#USA\n  | built = 1924\n  | architect = Wachendorff, Eugene C.\n  | architecture = Medieval eclectic\n  | added = March 18, 1986\n  | area = {{convert|21.4|acre}}\n  | governing_body = Local\n  | refnum = 86000437<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n| designated_other1_name = Atlanta Landmark Building\n| designated_other1_date = October 14, 1989\n| designated_other1_abbr = ALB\n| designated_other1_link = List of historic buildings and districts designated by the City of Atlanta\n| designated_other1_color= #aaccff\n}}\n\n'''Booker T. Washington High School''', named for the famous educator,<ref>{{cite web|title=Booker T. Washington, 1856-1915|url=http://docsouth.unc.edu/fpn/washington/bio.html|work=Documenting the American South|publisher=The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|accessdate=7 September 2011}}</ref> opened in September 1924 under the auspices of the [[Atlanta Board of Education]], with the late Charles Lincoln Harper as principal. It was the first public high school for [[African-American]]s in the [[Georgia (U.S. state)|state of Georgia]] and the [[Atlanta Public Schools]] system.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://apskids.org/washington/ Untitled Document<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nBooker T. Washington High School was transformed into four small schools. Starting in the fall of 2014, the school transitioned back to the original one school, with four assistant principals, one academy leader, and one principal.\n\n==Administration==\n* Angela Coaxum-Young, Principal\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Atlanta Trip 130.JPG|thumb|left]]\nDesigned by Atlanta-born architect [[Eugene C. Wachendorff]], the building incorporates medieval and Byzantine elements, including the dramatic main entrance with five arches in two tiers. Six additions have been made to the original four-story building, which is situated on {{convert|21.4|acre|m2}} of land. The building is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\nIt is fitting that visitors pass the statue of the school's namesake on the way to the entrance.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/atlanta/boo.htm|title=Booker T. Washington High School--Atlanta: A National Register of Historic Places Travel Itinerary|website=www.nps.gov|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> One of the foremost black educators of the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Booker T. Washington was born into slavery in 1856 on a small farm in Virginia. He founded the [[Tuskegee University|Tuskegee Institute]] in 1881. \n\nIn 1927, the only exact replica of the Booker T. Washington monument at [[Tuskegee University]] in Alabama was erected at the school's entrance. The statue of Washington, called \"Booker T. Washington Lifting the Veil of Ignorance,\" is a replica of the original bronze at the Tuskegee Institute by sculptor Charles Keck. The inscription reads: \"He lifted the veil of ignorance from his people and pointed the way to progress through education and industry.\" <ref name=\":0\" />\n\nToday, the school, which was placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1986, boasts an enrollment of more than 1600 students and a faculty and staff of more than 100.\n\nRecent visitors to the historic institution have included [[South Africa]]n Archbishop [[Desmond Tutu]], activist [[Jesse Jackson]], civil rights pioneer [[Rosa Parks]], and President [[George W. Bush]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2002/01/images/20020131-7-1.html|title=Visiting Martin Luther King's President alma mater, George W. Bush speaks to students, faculty and guests during a visit to Booker T. Washington High School in Atlanta, Ga. Jan 31, 2002. \"One way you can help is to find a child who needs somebody older in their life who can put their arm around them and say, \"I love you,\" \"There's hope for you,\" \"What can I do to help you succeed in America?'\" White House photo by Eric Draper.|website=georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/georgia/cascade/alma-powell-designates-booker-t-washington-high-as-fi633bf6e966|title=Alma Powell Designates Booker T. Washington High as First APS Promise Place School|date=2011-06-16|website=Cascade, GA Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nThe school serves as a cornerstone of Atlanta Public School's comprehensive reform program, Project GRAD (Graduation Really Achieves Dreams). The project aims to increase the number of inner city students who graduate and go to college.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Washington Early College===\nBooker T. Washington High School-Early College is one of the newest early college small schools in the Atlanta Public School System.  The premise behind the early college concept is to afford students the opportunity to obtain college credits while going to high school.  BTWHS-EC aims to prepare students to pursue post secondary education at some of the top universities and colleges in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlantapublicschools.us/domain/11274|title=Early College / Overview|last=|first=|date=|website=http|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the core program of study, students are required to take the following classes to meet the requirements of the Early College School:\n* Early College Seminar\n* Early College Math\n* Early College English\n* Early College Social Studies\n* Early College Science\n\n===Washington Banking, Finance, and Investment===\nThe Booker T. Washington High School Banking, Finance and Investment Small School (BFI) gives BTW high school students an opportunity to learn about and prepare for college careers in business and finance. Emphasis is placed on a college preparatory curriculum that is directly linked to the business world.\n\nThis school prepares students for careers in business and finance with challenging courses. It focuses on broad, transferable skills, with an emphasis on financial industry elements such as accounting, financial planning, management, banking, credit, economics, money management, technology, investments, and insurance. In addition to their required courses, BFI students take one or two specialized courses each semester and a college level course in their senior year. Students also participate in job shadowing experiences and paid internships.\n\nBFI is a part of the National Academy Foundation's Academy of Finance. This foundation assists in establishing an ongoing relationship that involves corporate executives, school personnel, parents, and students, and results in paid internships, scholarships, and employment opportunities. Students are provided opportunities to enter into paid internships with local financial service companies during the summer of their senior year, and many offers of part-time employment during the school year are provided.  BFI also has the Institute of Student Achievement (ISA) as its intermediary partner. This organization supports the school's planning process, curriculum development, leadership development, and overall development of the small learning communities.\n\n===Washington Health, Science, and Nutrition===\nThe Booker T. Washington High School of Health Science and Nutrition (BTWHSN) provides an interdisciplinary curriculum with a healthcare and nutrition concentration through in-depth investigation, hands-on discovery, experimentation, and inquiry-based learning. Through a four-year program of study, students have the opportunity to:\n\n* Undergo a rigorous and relevant curriculum and receive in-depth instruction designed to ensure that all students meet the graduation requirements of the Atlanta Public Schools system while affording them multiple opportunities for postsecondary study.\n* Gain college credit through dual enrollment and advanced placement courses.\n* Explore career interest in various nutrition and health care-related fields.\n* Gain invaluable knowledge, skills, and experiences through medical seminars, internships, and health science field trips.\n* Partake in an array of shadowing opportunities and hands-on modules.\n\nBooker T. Washington High School of Health Science and Nutrition offers two career pathways: Therapeutic Services and Nutrition & Food Science.\n\n==Feeder patterns==\n\n* Elementary schools: Herndon and Bethune\n* Middle schools: Kennedy, Sylvan, and Brown\n\n==Local School Council==\n\nThe property and business of the Booker T. Washington High School Local Council is managed by seven school council members, of whom two are parents or guardians of students enrolled in the school, two are teachers, and two are business education partners. The principal serves as chairperson of the Local School Council, which meets on the first Monday of each month from 9:00-10:00 am in the second-floor conference room at the school.<ref>[http://apskids.org/washington/Local%20School%20Council.htm Untitled Document<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Student activities==\n\n===Clubs and organizations===\n{{Div col|colwidth=27em}}\n* Academic Enrichment Team\n* Band/Auxiliaries\n* Bad-To-The-Bone Dance Team\n* [[Beta Club]]\n* Bulldog RAW (Recycling at Washington)\n* [[National Honor Society]]\n* Chess Club\n* Chorus\n* Dance Ensemble\n* Debate Team\n* [[Future Business Leaders of America]] (FBLA)\n* French Club\n* [[Future Educators of America]] (FEA)\n* [[Glee Club]]\n* [[Health Occupations Students of America]] (HOSA)\n* [[Mu Alpha Theta]] (Mathematics Honor Society)\n* Photography/Videography Club\n* Spanish Club\n* Stock Market\n* Student Government Association\n* Student Support Team\n* ''Washingtonian'' newspaper and yearbook team\n{{colend}}\n\n===Athletics===\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Football\n* Softball\n* Baseball\n* Track & field\n* Cross country\n* Cheerleading\n* Soccer\n* Volleyball\n* Golf\n* Basketball\n* Band\n* Swimming\n* Tennis<ref>[http://apskids.org/washington/Activities.htm Untitled Document<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\n===Religion===\n* [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] - civil rights leader\n\n===Arts and entertainment===\n* [[Lil Baby]] - rapper, singer\n* [[Raymond Andrews]] - novelist\n* [[Leslie C. Brown|Les Brown]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - motivational speaker\n* [[Bruce Bruce]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - actor, comedian\n* [[Lee Moses ]]<ref name=\"Alumni\"/> - musician\n* [[Jean Carne]]<ref name=\"Alumni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.btwbulldogs.com/Fame.html|title=Walk of Fame|publisher=btwBulldogs|accessdate=2009-05-02 | url-status=dead |archive-url=https: